Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 25th Weekly Dose of Optimism. After ta=
king a few weeks off for the holidays we=E2=80=99re ready to kick things of=
f with a big ole' Shot of Optimism [ https://substack.com/redirect/e80af21d=
-349f-4e35-b657-4f4f0e27054f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. This year is off to a strong start.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Composer [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/1221ed11-4123-4ac9-8cdd-e597601d573c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You know Composer, I love Composer =E2=80=94 the investing app that helps y=
ou achieve superior returns with logic and data. Since founding its algorit=
hmic trading platform in 2020, Composer has helped over 20,000 customers tr=
ade=C2=A0100s of millions of dollars. I=E2=80=99m one of them =E2=80=94 my =
Composer portfolio is actually up since I started using it last year, which=
 is incredible because the portfolio of individual stocks I own is =E2=80=
=A6 not.=20
Here=E2=80=99s what I like about using Composer:
The product combines beauty and power =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s my favorite in=
vesting UX
Automation, rebalancing, and conditional rules mean I can take emotion out =
of it
I can copy smarter peoples=E2=80=99 Symphonies, tweak them, build my own, a=
nd backtest them all
It=E2=80=99s a much simpler way to build a balanced, diversified portfolio =
than I could on my own
(1) Announcing Not Boring Capital Fund III [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
eebd699a-d277-4290-a1b8-fde5dfdf0eae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy McCormick [ https://substack.com/redirect/3cbfa529-03e9-45b0-95c2-c69=
3a149c83b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] for Not Boring
Companies founded in this decade will shape humanity=E2=80=99s trajectory f=
or the next century. Some people are pessimistic about that trajectory =E2=
=80=93 AI will kill us all, the planet will burn. We are unabashedly optimi=
stic about that trajectory, not in the sense that everything will be perfec=
t, but in the sense that humans have agency, acquire new knowledge, and sha=
pe the future we want. Technology companies will have an important role to =
play in shaping it, and tremendous value to capture from the trillions of d=
ollars shaken loose when they do.
There=E2=80=99s not much to add to what Packy wrote in the Fund III announc=
ement (he=E2=80=99s not one who generally leaves words on the table), but i=
f you haven=E2=80=99t had the chance to read it already, I encourage you to=
 do so. On the surface, it=E2=80=99s a fund investment thesis. At it=E2=80=
=99s core, it=E2=80=99s just another manifestation of Packy=E2=80=99s gener=
al worldview.
The world is on a long, upward sloping path towards progress and we should =
be optimistic, despite the inevitable obstacles, about that trajectory.
Here=E2=80=99s how I=E2=80=99ve started to view the Not Boring Flywheel, an=
d the Weekly Dose of Optimism=E2=80=99s place within it:
Not Boring Newsletter: Analyzes the innovative business strategies and comp=
anies that are shaping humanity=E2=80=99s trajectory over the next century
Weekly Dose of Optimism: Celebrates the achievements of individuals, teams,=
 and organizations that are shaping that trajectory
Not Boring Capital: Invests in the companies that are shaping that trajecto=
ry
Not Boring Founders: Amplifies the founders that are shaping that trajector=
y
Let=E2=80=99s keep this flywheel spinnin=E2=80=99!
(2) FDA Grants Accelerated Approval for Alzheimer=E2=80=99s Disease Treatme=
nt [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c094669-f77b-40c9-90f3-68691ec01444?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From the FDA
Leqembi was approved using the Accelerated Approval pathway [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/861b69cb-9dd2-4914-8f2c-0ba6328fd72b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], under which the FDA may ap=
prove drugs for serious conditions where there is an unmet medical need and=
 a drug is shown to have an effect on a surrogate endpoint that is reasonab=
ly likely to predict a clinical benefit to patients. The results of a Phase=
 3 randomized, controlled clinical trial to confirm the drug's clinical ben=
efit have recently been reported and the agency anticipates receiving the d=
ata soon.
We=E2=80=99ve written at length as to why Alzheimer=E2=80=99s treatments ar=
e important to us =E2=80=94 it runs in our family, it impacts tens of milli=
ons of families world wide, and it=E2=80=99s generally just one of the shit=
tier disease to experience, first or second hand. Packy=E2=80=99s fear of A=
lzheimer=E2=80=99s is what drove him to start writing in the first place.
The FDA recently approved Leqempi, a promising Alzheimer=E2=80=99s treatmen=
t, for Accelerated Approval. And while the approval was not met without cri=
ticism =E2=80=94 look what happened with Aduhelm [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/f4e4557b-0dc0-4c1d-b767-6c1117fae39a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], it=E2=80=99s too expensive, it doesn=
=E2=80=99t help all Alzhiemer=E2=80=99s patients, more data is needed =E2=
=80=94 we are generally supportive of common sense accelerated approvals on=
 treatments that could have a meaningful impact on quality of life, especia=
lly when the alternative is =E2=80=9Cno alternative.=E2=80=9D
(3) Risk of Dying from Cancer Continues to Drop at an Accelerated Pace [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/a7f2c6ac-fd57-4de5-89eb-7a0521e28a4c?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From The American Cancer Society
The 32% drop in cancer death rate between 1991 and 2019 translates to almos=
t 3.5 million fewer cancer deaths during these years than what would have b=
een expected if the death rate had not fallen. This success is largely beca=
use of fewer people smoking, which resulted in declines in lung and other s=
moking-related cancers [ https://substack.com/redirect/2aef80d4-6309-42dd-b=
3b0-6a6f3ba4f919?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ].
Packy and I spoke to a founder on Wednesday that surprised us when he said,=
 =E2=80=9CThere is already a cure for cancer. It=E2=80=99s early detection.=
=E2=80=9D While there=E2=80=99s no silver bullet, early detection has been =
one of the leading drivers of declining cancer death rates over the last 30=
 years.
According to a new report published by the American Cancer Society, during =
the last 30 years there=E2=80=99s been a 32% decrease in cancer mortality r=
ates which have resulted in an estimated 3.5 million fewer cancer deaths. W=
hat that means in practice is that a handful of people that you know haven=
=E2=80=99t died from cancer that would have in earlier generations. This de=
cline is largely due to a combination of less smoking, earlier detection, a=
nd improved therapeutics.=20
(4) In Lebanon, Solar Power Is Booming. Why? [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/d8c2f97d-b5ee-4f24-916c-6f360e6f7f78?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Kristin V. Monroe [ https://substack.com/redirect/0d6d285c-2393-4201-8acd-7=
89205199494?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for Sapiens
Still, there is, undeniably, something brightening about Lebanon=E2=80=99s =
solar panels. As Younis=E2=80=99 story reveals, the panels are a double-edg=
ed sword: In financing their own solutions to economic and political breakd=
own, many Lebanese are becoming further burdened by debt. But by enabling p=
eople to power their households, solar panels have also helped restore some=
 normalcy and alleviate hardship=E2=80=94allowing people to reclaim dignity=
 lost during the country=E2=80=99s collapse.
At a macro-level, we=E2=80=99ve written extensively about the plummeting co=
st of solar (solar kWh from $0.42 in 2009 to $0.05 in 2021) due to learning=
 curves. This is one of the more important stories in energy, and therefore=
 in the world, of the last few years. So it=E2=80=99s cool to see the impac=
t of solar at the more micro-level, as we are seeing in Lebanon. Lebanon=E2=
=80=99s economy is struggling, the currency has lost 90% of its value in th=
ree years, there is a devastating energy shortage, and, or course, politica=
l turmoil =E2=80=94 and against this backdrop, individuals are left to powe=
r (literally) their own lives. Some have turned to generators and others, i=
ncreasingly commonly, have turned towards solar.
As the writer notes, it=E2=80=99s tempting to view this as an optimistic st=
ory. The Beiruti people are resilient and, perhaps, even super environmenta=
lly conscious. But below the surface, the story is a bit darker =E2=80=94 i=
t=E2=80=99s a story of what happens when a state fails to provide basic uti=
lities like electricity. If nothing else, it shows that decentralized solut=
ions can work when the centralized one falls short. People are resilient.=20
(5) Riddle solved: Why was Roman concrete so durable? [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/ce234cd6-bbee-40c6-8ded-418d0f964d16?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
David L. Chandler [ https://substack.com/redirect/8cbe549b-e401-4354-b20b-9=
2557e91eb1f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for MIT News
Under closer examination, these ancient samples also contain small, distinc=
tive, millimeter-scale bright white mineral features, which have been long =
recognized as a ubiquitous component of Roman concretes. These white chunks=
, often referred to as =E2=80=9Clime clasts,=E2=80=9D originate from lime, =
another key component of the ancient concrete mix.
A team of researchers recently discovered the secret to ancient Roman struc=
tures=E2=80=99 durability, and that secret could be beneficial in the devel=
opment of more durable, lighter-weight, and ultimately environmentally frie=
ndlier concretes today. Without getting too much into the details, what wer=
e previously thought to be little white blemishes in ancient concrete are a=
ctually the signs of a sophisticated concrete mixing process called =E2=80=
=9Cquickliming.=E2=80=9D The lead researcher had been confounded that the o=
therwise meticulous ancient builders would allow for such blemishes, unless=
 they held a deeper purposes =E2=80=94 and it turns out, his suspicion was =
on point.
Material science will be increasingly important over the next few decades a=
s we generate and harness more energy, explore foreign terrains, and build =
increasingly advanced structures. And as this story reminds us, when buildi=
ng for the future, it=E2=80=99s always wise to understand the past.
Bonus: Not Boring Founders: Nicholas Chadwick, Mission Zero Technologies [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/6d793d48-7f0e-4abb-bee0-53392335d78a?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy sat down with Nicholas Chadwick, founder and CEO of Mission Zero Tech=
nologies. MZT is developing direct air capture (DAC) technology that will r=
ecover high-purity CO2 from the air while incurring only a fraction of the =
costs and energy it takes to do so today. We were first put in touch with N=
ick and the team by Frontier, the Advanced Market Commitment run by Stripe,=
 Shopify, Meta and others.
P.S. =E2=80=94 We also dropped the world premier of =E2=80=9CShot of Optimi=
sm [ https://substack.com/redirect/e80af21d-349f-4e35-b657-4f4f0e27054f?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=
=9D at the top of this episode. We apologize in advance that it=E2=80=99ll =
be in your head all day. s/o Yung Spielberg!
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am E=
ST on Monday morning.
Thanks for reading,
Dan

